{
  "text": "Similar problems arise when conducting OLS-regressions with the study's second dependent variable, interactivity, due to its distributional characteristics. Within the framework of generalized linear models (GLzM, see [CITATION_1] , regression models can easily be adjusted to such data situations. When faced with nonnegative responses that are greater than zero, have a high initial peak, a rapid drop and a long right tail (as is the case with the interactivity outcome), the gamma distribution is preferred to model the outcome (Hardin and Hilbe, 2007: 89ff) . Therefore, hypothesis testing was based on a gamma model using ML-estimation. The hypotheses were tested by assessing improvements in model fit in the news factors over the baseline models using likelihood ratio tests (LR-tests) between nested models (cf. Long and Freese, 2006: 99ff) .",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "116961171"
  },
